<p>Before the World Wide Web became the dominant public face of life online, many people first encountered computer-mediated communication through the bulletin board system, or BBS. For a generation of users, the BBS was not merely a tool but a place: a local digital hangout, a software exchange, a message board, a social club, a technical resource, and in many cases a gateway into the wider world of networked culture. To understand the history of the early Internet properly, it is essential to understand the BBS era that ran alongside it and, in many ways, helped prepare ordinary people for online life.</p>

